--------------------------------------------------------------------------

<u>Darling International Inc. (DAR)</u>

This one fits in with my AG theme. Schwab's Equity rating on this company is a
"C" - Market Perform as of 10/7/2011. There was a pretty large insider sale in
August 2011 at $15.80/share for 89K shares. BV is 7.35/share so at current
prices the company sells at 1.79X BV. Sales growth over the last 5 years was
18.6%. EPS growth over the last 5 years was a respectable 34.8%. Therefore, it
appears they were able to achieve margin expansion over this period through
efficiency and/or higher end product/service prices.

<u>I do like their high margin business: Gross Margin @ 30% ; Operating Margin
@ 17.2%; Net Profit Margin @ 9.2%</u>. ROA is 13.0% and ROE is 20.5% both
respectable returns. The company has shown good double digit growth in both
earnings and sales over the last five years.

<u>The company carries a lot of goodwill ($3.21/share) as a result of their
$840M Griffin Industries Inc. acquisition</u>.
(http://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/news/2010/11/09/griffin-industries-acqui
ed-for-840m.html ). This amount on their balance sheet is almost as much as the
line item for property plant and equipment. I was interested to see if they own
or lease their processing facilities.

From their 10K:

"...As of January 1, 2011, the Company operates over 125 processing and
transfer facilities including the processing locations listed below. <u>All of
the processing facilities are owned except for ten leased facilities and the
Company owns or leases over 60 transfer stations in the U.S., some of which
also process yellow grease and trap. </u>These transfer stations serve as
collection points for routing raw material to the processing facilities ...".

(Note: Substantially all assets of the Company, including real property, are
either pledged or mortgaged as collateral for borrowings under the Company's
Senior Secured Credit Facilities. )

So, they have real property assets which are probably carried at cost but are
mortgage for borrowing under their credit facility. The company has been paying
down this credit facility which adds directly to BV.

Paul is correct that this is a capital intensive business. I see they carry
$250M of long term (Note due 2018) fixed debt paying 8.5% and $300M term
loan(s) priced at various variable interest rates.

On January 27, 2011, the company sold 24,193,548 shares (diluted current shares
by 21%) at a price of $12.70 per share. This resulted in $307M. $140M of the
proceeds was used to pay down their term loan facility (from $300M to $160M).
The remaining reduced their floating credit facility.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
---------

<u>This one is on my watch list and I will look to add shares below their
secondary stock offering price of $12.70/share. </u>The company still has a lot
of debt at fairly high rates (8.5%). Their recent acquisition resulted in over
a $3.00/share Goodwill balance sheet adjustment which to me carries no "real"
tangible value.

Their overall operation(s) brings more efficiency into the back end food
(waste) processing business but it is not clear to me if such operations should
be integrated with the current farm operation(s) first (similar to what SEB is
now doing on their Hog farms). DAR's network of regional processing facilities
does serve a niche market but does not seem to me to be a growth industry
except for adding new "waste" processing segments like they have done with
acquiring Griffin Industries Inc. and also by building their bakery segment.

<u>Therefore, I am on the fence with this one unless it can be purchased at a
bargain price.</u> If after a year their consolidated operations can book a PE
less than 10x and still maintain their double digit EPS growth, that might
provide a good "value" entry point. Eventually after 3 years of similar
results, PE expansion (reflecting growth rate) might eventually be priced into
the stock.

EKS
