re: DAR

Hi EKS,

I'm going to spend some serious time on this. I haven't dug deep into its 10K's
yet, as my wife signed me up to participate in a church event and the
rehearsals have been consuming me... So, take whatever I said below with a
grain of salt.

DAR looks like a growth story to me, with strong moats. While it's capital
intensive, it appears its facilities don't required a lot of maintenance capex.
Growing + Moats + Low Capex. Isn't that the holy grail for value investors?!
This is like Buffett's toll booth, but the things got moved around are not cars
but grease waste and the likes.

I read that Griffin's network doesn't overlap much with DAR's. And Griffin is
more profitable than DAR. While I also don't like the goodwill on the book, I
sense strong synergy here. And DAR's track record of integrating its previous
acquisition looks good.

My main concern is its profit is linked to ag commodity and fuel prices, and
this is not in my circle of competence. I still don't have a good sense where
we are in the cycle. (Did you say Ag sector is currently depressed? Why? Would
you mind to remind me?)

Its beta is 1.9! I think if there is any bad news from Europe in the coming
months, we will have good opportunity to buy this cheaper.
